[1] Bolivia
Date: Sat 16 Feb 2008
Source: RTE News [edited]
<http://www.rte.ie/news/2008/0216/bolivia.html>


A 19-year-old man in Bolivia has died from dengue fever, marking the
1st death from the disease since massive floods began ravaging the
country in November [2008]. The teenager who died was from the
northwest part of Bolivia, among the areas hardest hit by the
torrential rains that have killed 53 people nationwide. [The floods
occurred in the northeastern Bolivian tropical lowlands, not the
northwest. - Mods.TY/JW]

With more than 100 cases of dengue fever recorded around the country,
authorities have issued health warnings, fearing epidemics due to
persistent flooding.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Brent Barrett

[With flooding concentrating the rodent host of Machupo virus,
_Calomys callosus_, the etiologic agent of Bolivian Hemorrhagic
fever, into higher ground where human settlements are found, one
suspects that the risk of this serious disease will also increase. -
Mods.JW/TY]

[A relief map of Bolivia can be accessed at:
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/bolivia_rel_2006.jpg>. - Mod.TY]

******
[2] Brazil (Rio de Janeiro)
Date: Fri 15 Feb 2008
Source: O Globo Online [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://oglobo.globo.com/rio/mat/2008/02/15/numero_de_vitimas_da_dengue_quatro_vezes_de_janeiro_de_2007-425682832.asp>


This season will be known as the summer of dengue. The number of
cases of the disease has grown frighteningly: the number of
notifications of [cases occurring in] the month of January [2008] has
reached 4290, an increase of 1110 cases since Thursday [14 Feb 2008].
Already, there 4 times more victims of the mosquito _Aedes aegypti_
in the city than were registered in January of last year [2007]. In
February [2008], there have already been 205 patients recorded,
totaling 4495 victims since the beginning of the year, more than
January and February 2007 together (2935).

The situation is worrying. If the dengue [cases] continue growing at
this pace, there is the risk of an epidemic, says Victor Berbara,
superintendent of Public Health of the state. According to Victor,
one of the reasons for the great concern is not just the number of
cases but the severity of them. The disease has affected more
children, susceptible to dengue virus 2, which is again circulating.
Half of the dengue hospitalizations are people up to 14 years, said Victor.

According to the superintendent, the summer is propitious for the
proliferation of mosquitoes. The recent rains have fostered the
emergence of outbreaks. This week, the [vector mosquito] eggs will
hatch. We will have more mosquitoes in circulation. The situation is
more critical in Curicica, where 578 cases of the disease have been
recorded this year [2008].

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT <promed@promedmail.org>

[It appears that Rio is off to another year of active dengue virus
transmission and cases. A map showing the location of Rio de Janeiro
can be accessed at:
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/brazil.jpg>, and an
interactive map showing the location of Curicica on the coast can be
accessed at: <http://www.tageo.com/index-e-br-v-21-d-545818.htm>. - Mod.TY]

******
[3] Indonesia (Java)
Date: Sat 16 Feb 2008
Source: Antara [edited]
<http://www.antara.co.id/en/arc/2008/2/16/dengue-kills-37-in-c-java/>


At least 37 people died of dengue fever in Central Java province
during January 2008, a local official said.

According to the record of the Central Java provincial
administration, there were 2347 cases of dengue fever in January
2008, a decrease from 2518 cases, with 62 fatalities in January 2007,
Hartanto, the head of the Central Java Health Service, said here on
Saturday [16 Feb 2008].

During the 1st 2 weeks of February 2008, at least 57 local people
were infected with the dengue fever virus.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED Rapporteur Brent Barrett

[Rapporteur Barrett also sent a similar article in Antara News
(<http://www.antara.co.id/en/arc/2008/2/17/news-focus-dengue-breaks-out-in-java-again/>)
reporting dengue in Central Java that also contained information
about dengue having also broken out in another area outside Java. In
Manado, North Sulawesi, for example, the disease has affected almost
all subdistricts in the town. Head of Manado's Health Service, Dr
Alex Turangan, said in the 1st 6 weeks of 2008, the _Aedes
aegepti_-transmitted virus had infected 154 people, one of whom died.

An interactive map of Indonesia showing the location of Java can be
accessed at:
<http://encarta.msn.com/map_701513467/java_sea.html>. - Mod.TY]

