[6] Cambodia (correction)
Date: 12 Feb 2008
From: Tom Kiedrzynsk <tomk@spc.int>


Re: The ProMED post on dengue in Cambodia (archive no.
20080120.0255), in 2007, 407 Cambodian people died out of some [40
000] dengue fever cases, or 38 000 cases and 389 deaths, which gives
a CFR of approximately one percent, not 10 percent.

--
Dr Tom Kiedrzynski
Epidemiologist
SPC PO Box D5
98848 Noumea cedex
New Caledonia
<tomk@spc.int>

[ProMED thanks Dr. Kiedrzynski for alertly spotting our error and
calling it to our attention. Dr. Jody Lenard <jody@psandman.com> of
the Peter Sandman Risk Communication Website initiative also called
our attention to this error. - Mod.TY]

******
[7] Sri Lanka
Date: Sun 17 Feb 2008
Source: The Sunday Times Online [edited]
<http://www.sundaytimes.lk/080217/News/news0016.html>


Three deaths attributed to dengue have been reported during the 1st
45 days of the year [2008] in Trincomalee. According to the
Trincomalee Medical Officer of Health, Dr. Sathiskumar, 34 persons
have contracted dengue this year [2008]. The 3 deaths attributed to
dengue have caused panic among the people and public health staff in
the Trincomalee district.

Preventive measures such as spraying pesticide along roads in town
are among the measures taken to stop the spread of this disease.
Sanitary employees too have been employed to inspect every house and
to collect discarded empty coconut shells, bottles, and tires, which
are considered breeding grounds for the dengue mosquito, public
health officials said. There were no deaths due to dengue in the year
2007, although 47 persons contracted the fever. In the year 2006,
only 3 out of 36 patients died due to the disease.

[Byline: Sinniah Gurunathan]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

